# Kill Switch — {{team_name}}

> Emergency stop mechanism. Three independent triggers; any of them
> halts the entire team within one cron tick. Build session implements
> all three.

## What "kill switch" means

A persistent signal that, once set, causes EVERY agent's wake to
short-circuit before doing any work. Agents check the signal at the
start of every wake (after env load, before any tool calls).

This protects against runaway loops, leaked credentials, compromised
state, and "I'm panicking, just stop everything" moments. Recovery
requires explicit human action — the team does not self-resume.

## Three triggers

The team is halted if ANY of these conditions hold:

### 1. File flag

```
.agentbloc/KILL_SWITCH
```

If this file exists, the team is halted. Create with:

```bash
touch .agentbloc/KILL_SWITCH
```

Remove with:

```bash
rm .agentbloc/KILL_SWITCH
```

The file's contents are ignored; existence is the signal.

### 2. Environment variable

```
AGENTBLOC_KILL=1
```

If this env var is set to `1`, the team is halted. Use this when the
file flag is impractical (e.g., team is in a remote container and you
can't shell in). Set in `.env` and the next cron tick honors it.

### 3. Telegram slash-command

```
/halt-all <reason>
```

In the team's escalations Telegram thread, this command from an
authorized user (per `.env`'s `TELEGRAM_AUTHORIZED_USERS`) creates
the file flag. Reverse with `/resume-all`.

This is the most ergonomic kill switch for non-technical operators —
they don't need shell access, just Telegram.

## How agents check

Every agent's wake (or the runtime's wake wrapper) executes this
contract before any other work:

```bash
# pseudocode — adapt to runtime
if [ -f ".agentbloc/KILL_SWITCH" ] || [ "$AGENTBLOC_KILL" = "1" ]; then
  audit_log "kill_switch_fire" "agent=$AGENT_ID reason=flag-set"
  exit 0   # silent exit; no telegram noise (the kill IS the alarm)
fi
```

The reference impl `runtime/reference-impl/wake.sh` does this in its
preamble. Hook order: kill-switch ALWAYS precedes any other PreToolUse
hook (alphabetical naming `00-kill-switch-check.sh` ensures this).

## Why "silent exit"

When the kill switch fires, the team is broken or under attack. Sending
hundreds of Telegram alarms compounds the problem. The kill switch
itself IS the alarm — the operator who set it knows. Subsequent silence
confirms agents stopped.

The ONE exception: if the kill switch fires due to detection logic
(e.g., audit-log pattern detection), the detector that fires it sends
ONE Telegram alarm before silencing further notifications.

## Recovery

To resume:

1. Investigate why the kill switch fired (read recent audit log,
   approvals.jsonl, and escalations.jsonl)
2. Fix the underlying issue
3. Remove the file flag: `rm .agentbloc/KILL_SWITCH`
4. Or unset the env var, or send `/resume-all`
5. Manually trigger one wake of one agent to verify the team is healthy
6. Let cron resume normal operation

The team does NOT self-recover. Operator-driven recovery is the point.

## Detection-driven kills (optional, v3.0+)

The build session may add automated kill triggers based on patterns:

| Trigger | Detector | Why |
|---|---|---|
| Cost spike | Cost > threshold per cron interval | Runaway agent burning $ |
| Audit-log anomaly | Same correlation_id appearing > N times | Loop detected |
| External error rate | Tool failures > X% in window | Vendor outage cascade |
| Approval timeout cascade | More than N pending approvals | Operator unresponsive |

Each detector lives as an optional cron job that touches
`.agentbloc/KILL_SWITCH` on detection. Out-of-the-box: none of these
are enabled. Build session enables per team risk profile.

## Tests

Build session writes tests asserting:

1. With file flag set, every agent's wake exits 0 immediately
2. With env var set, same
3. Removing the flag + waking an agent succeeds
4. The kill-switch hook runs BEFORE other PreToolUse hooks
5. Kill-switch fire emits exactly one audit log line, no Telegram

## What NOT to do

- Don't auto-resume after a timeout — defeats the purpose
- Don't skip the kill check to "save a cycle" — the check is cheap
- Don't tie the kill to a single trigger — defense in depth requires
  three independent triggers

